pare   Ale   and   Alma   4.","Swedish: variant of   Ahl  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ale","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos Enrique, Cesar, Jose, Maria De Jesus.","Spanish (Andalusia; <b>Alé</b>): unexplained.","Italian (Sicily; <b>Alé</b>): probably a variant of   Aleo  ."]}]},{"name":"Iorwerth,","type":"LAST","meanings":["A Cornish form of Edward."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Cheng, Jing, Kam Fung, Wai Shing, Wing, Yali, Yuk.","Chinese:","variant Romanization of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Ou","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ying, Ching, Heng, Hong, Jia, Kuang Yu, Li-Ching, Cho, Chong, Chung, Sa.  Southeast Asian Lichun, Ming, Quan, Roeun, Sokhom, Chau, Hai, Leang, Ly, Nhanh, Phan, Pho, Tha.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 歐, meaning ‘to sing someone's praise’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the placename Dong Ou (東甌), a fief (in present-day Wenzhou in Zhejiang province) which was granted to Yao in 192  BC . It is said that Yao was a descendant of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the placename Ou Yu (歐餘), the name of a fief (located in present-day Zhejiang province) that was granted to Ti, the second son of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 區, originally denoting an ancient vessel for measurement in ancient Chinese: from the personal name of <i>Ou Zhizi</i> (歐治子), an expert sword-maker who lived during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). Some of his descendants inherited <i>Ou</i> (歐) as their surname, simplifying the Chinese character 歐 to 區."]}]},{"name":"Gwent","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Ghent (<i>Gent</i> in Dutch), a city in Flanders, Belgium. Compare   Gent  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gent","meanings":["English (northern) and French: nickname from Old French <i>gent</i>, Middle English <i>gent(e)</i> ‘high born, noble’, hence ‘noble of character or conduct, courteous’, also ‘nice, friendly’.","English: habitational name from Ghent (<i>Gent</i> in Dutch), a city in Flanders, Belgium. Compare   Ghent  .","German: from a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with <i>gand</i> ‘spell’, such as <i>Gandolf</i>."]},{"name":"Ghant","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Ghent  , a habitational name for someone from Ghent in Flanders. This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical.  See  <b>Adam</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adam ab Iorwerth, of Gwent was born in 1190, his father, lorwerth ap Caradog, was 31 and his mother, Alis verch Bleddyn Broadspear, was 15. He had at least 5 sons and 1 daughter with LORWERN-ap CRAIG. He died in 1246, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1190–1246":"1190–1246","1190–1260":"1190–1260","1200–1295":"1200–1295","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1214–1246":"1214–1246","1216–1278":"1216–1278","1220–1228":"1220–1228","1225–0012":"1225–0012","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","1242–1268":"1242–1268","1160–1250":"1160–1250","1175–1255":"1175–1255","1190":"1190","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1175":"1175","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1160":"1160","1228":"1228","1216":"1216","1214":"1214","1225":"1225","1246":"1246","1268":"1268","1278":"1278","1255":"1255","1200":"1200","0012":"0012","before 1190":"enne 1190","Europe":"Europe","England":"England"},"fi":{"1190–